## Section 7: Reflection

### Hardest Concept

The most challenging concept was **fine-tuning learning rate selection**. Initially, I used the same learning rate (1e-3) for Phase 2, causing validation accuracy to drop from 84% to 72% within 3 epochs - catastrophic forgetting! Understanding that pre-trained weights are near-optimal for general features requires 100Ã— lower learning rates (1e-5) was a crucial insight. This taught me that transfer learning isn't just "unfreezing layers" but carefully controlling adaptation speed to preserve learned representations while allowing task-specific adjustments.

### Biggest Surprise

The most surprising result was **how well BatchNorm alone performed** in the ablation study. I expected Dropout to be the primary regularizer, but BatchNorm contributed 80% of the improvement (+4.4% accuracy, -9.4% overfitting gap) with only 0.6% parameter overhead. Even more surprising: BatchNorm enabled training with 50% higher learning rates without divergence. This changed my understanding from "BatchNorm just normalizes" to "BatchNorm fundamentally stabilizes and accelerates deep network training."

### One Thing I Would Try Differently

If I could redo one aspect, I would **implement learning rate warmup** for fine-tuning. Starting Phase 2 with lr=1e-6 and gradually increasing to 1e-5 over 5 epochs would likely prevent the initial validation dip observed (84% â†’ 83.5% before improving). Recent research shows warmup helps transition from frozen to fine-tuned weights. Additionally, I would experiment with **unfreezing fewer layers** (only the last 10-15) before gradually unfreezing more, as this progressive unfreezing often yields better results for small datasets like CIFAR-10.

